Introduction

Handwashing and Clean Water: Essential to Saving Lives Directly tying in with the 6th United Nations Sustainable Development Goal, and the UNICEF Millenium Development Goal 7C, calling for â€˜sustainable accessâ€™ to â€˜basic sanitationâ€™, the WHO/UNICEF Joint Monitoring Programme (JMP) developed a metric of the use of â€˜improvedâ€™ sanitation facilities, providing a means of clean water that can be used for personal hygiene. This metric has been recorded and developed since the year 2000, addressing the human right and need to have a source of clean water that is safe to use and consume. Furthermore, this also tracks and takes into account the management of human faecal waste, as any discharge or contamination of otherwise safe water resources is considered a serious public hazard.

The Importance of Availability of Clean Water and Soap Handwashing with soap and water is one of the easiest and most effective ways to prevent the spread of diseases. Itâ€™s a simple habit that can make a serious difference in protecting our health. However today, approximately 2.2 billion people around the world do not have safely managed drinking water. While the world has seen great improvement in this issue over the years, there are still millions of people, especially in rural or low-income areas, that still lack this essential resource. Without the availability of proper handwashing facilities, the risk of illness particularly infectious diseases, such as diarrhoea, cholera, and hepatitis, become significantly higher.

Code 
import polars as pl
from plotnine import *


df = (
    pl.read_csv("/content/unicef_indicator_1-2.csv")
      .select([
          pl.col("country"),
          pl.col("time_period").cast(pl.Int32).alias("year"),
          pl.col("obs_value").alias("observed_value"),
      ])
)

df2022 = (
    df
    .filter(pl.col("year") == 2022)
    .sort("observed_value", descending=True)
)

plot_df = df2022.to_pandas()

(
    ggplot(plot_df, aes(
        x='reorder(country, -observed_value)',
        y='observed_value'
    ))
    + geom_col()
    + labs(
        title="Observed Value per Country in 2022",
        x="Country",
        y="Observed Value"
    )
    + theme_minimal()
    + theme(
        axis_text_x=element_text(rotation=90, hjust=1),
        figure_size=(12, 6)
    )
)

A Lack of Progress in the Most Critical Places Alarmingly, and despite close surveying over 20 years, it appears as though the worst-performing countries when it comes to having available sanitary water and handwashing facilities in households, show the least progress as time progresses. In this line graph, the 10 countries with the least average access to means of sanitation show staggeringly little progress over the years. These countries include Burundi, Comoros, Ethiopia, Gambia, Guinea-Bissau, Lesotho, Liberia, Mali, Mozambique and South Sudan. What do all these countries have in common that leads to this desperate situation? Most of these countries feature overall weak infrastructure, staggeringly high poverty rates, limited access to resources and great political instability and conflict. This makes it so that supplying the people who live in these countries with clean water and soap is very challenging, while there also isnâ€™t many people who can afford to use these resources. Because of the major political instability, a number of these countries have been left completely war-torn, making any hope of the situation getting better all the more dire.

The Relation Between GDP and Sanitation in Households From the above graphs, we can see both the overall percentage of households with safe water for sanitation, year by year, along with the average GDP per capita superimposed over each country on a heat map. With this, it can be seen that there is a clear correlation between a countryâ€™s ability to use clean water for sanitary purposes and their overall economic health, where countries with higher levels of domestic production and wealth perform better than those without. Countries such as the USA, Canada, UK, Germany, France, Japan and South Korea have close to 100% access to handwashing facilities with soap and clean water. Their higher GDP per capita allows their governments to invest in sanitation so that households are able to afford soap and running water. Many Sub-Saharan African countries, parts of South Asia, and conflict-ridden nations on the other hand, have less than 50% access, with some even falling below 10%. This includes countries such as Burundi, Liberia, South Sudan, and Mozambique. These countries are suffering from a lack of resources to invest in developing improved infrastructure for facilities such as clean running water, and for developing hygiene education, to raise awareness over the importance of practices such as handwashing.

Vital for Maintaining Health and Fighting Disease Thereâ€™s also a distinct correlation between a countryâ€™s average life expectancy and a countryâ€™s households means and access to soap and clean, running water. Without the ability or resources to practice proper handwashing, people within a country are far more vulnerable to infectious diseases that can be life threatening. Not only does a lack of ability to practice good hygiene lead to vulnerability to infectious diseases, but also contracting these diseases more frequently. This leads to more long-term issues such as malnutrition, weakened immune systems which in turn, reduces a countryâ€™s workforce productivity. All of these issues, in time, further impact a countryâ€™s economic stability and chance of improving their potential healthcare and sanitary crisis. This shows just how important a means of hygiene is to the well-being and livelihood of a countryâ€™s people, and for the country as a whole, on an economic and developmental level.

Code 
import pandas as pd
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_point, theme_minimal, labs

ind_df  = pd.read_csv('/content/unicef_indicator_1-2.csv')
meta_df = pd.read_csv('/content/unicef_metadata-2.csv')

handwash = (
    ind_df
    .groupby('country', as_index=False)['obs_value']
    .mean()
    .rename(columns={'obs_value':'avg_handwash'})
)
lifeexp  = (
    meta_df
    .groupby('country', as_index=False)['Life expectancy at birth, total (years)']
    .mean()
    .rename(columns={'Life expectancy at birth, total (years)':'avg_lifeexp'})
)

df = (
    handwash
    .merge(lifeexp, on='country', how='inner')
    .dropna()
)

(
    ggplot(df, aes(x='avg_handwash', y='avg_lifeexp'))
    + geom_point(size=2)
    + labs(
        x='Avg handwashing facility availability (%)',
        y='Avg life expectancy at birth (years)',
        title='Life Expectancy vs. Handwashing Coverage by Country'
    )
    + theme_minimal()
)

Access to Clean Water is a Human Right The links observed betwen handwashing, GDP and life expectancy, as well as the alarming lack of improvement over the past two decades is a reminder of the vital need for the capacity to practice good hygiene, with access to clean and properly managed water and soap. Basic hygiene is the simplest way to control the spread of disease and ensure a good quality of life for all, and most certainly should not be considered a privilege. However, looking at the statistical situation of many countries at a disadvantage, it appears as though access to such means of personal hygiene are indeed a privilege. Working together in a worldwide collective effort to provide the countries whose people are not capable of maintaining their health, can save millions of lives and increase the global capability to combat diseases.
